			<article class="post-2014 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook" id="post-2014">
                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Hedge Fund Sues U.S. Prosecutor</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Sydney Ember                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-02-27T12:23:11+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 27, 2015 7:23 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 27, 2015 7:23 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/morning-agenda-hedge-fund-sues-u-s-prosecutor/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Hedge Fund Sues U.S. Prosecutor" data-description="A hedge fund is fighting back against Preet Bharara. | Standard Chartered overhauls its leadership. | Hedge funds are still attracting money from big investors. | K.K.R.-backed Samson Resources hires restructuring advisers.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong> HEDGE FUND SUES U.S. PROSECUTOR</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> More than four years and dozens of insider trading convictions after F.B.I. agents staged a surprise raid of three hedge funds â feeding the national reputation of the prosecutor Preet Bharara as the new sheriff of Wall Street â one of those funds is fighting back, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/dealbook/fbi-warrant-in-insider-trading-cases-is-unsealed.html">Matthew Goldstein, Ben Protess and Andrew Ross Sorkin report in DealBook</a>. On Thursday, David Ganek, a Manhattan socialite and art collector whose $4 billion Level Global was one of the funds raided, sued Mr. Bharara, the United States attorney in Manhattan, contending that official misconduct violated his constitutional rights.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhile legal experts said <b>Mr. Ganekâs lawsuit could be a long shot</b>, it comes at a time when Mr. Bhararaâs image as an invincible prosecutor â racking up convictions on Wall Street and setting his sights on Albanyâs power brokers â is beginning to fray,â DealBook writes. Recently, for instance, a federal appeals court ruling overturned the convictions of two hedge fund traders, including Anthony Chiasson, Mr. Ganekâs partner at Level Global.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ganekâs lawsuit was filed just hours after the confidential warrant was unsealed by a federal judge at the request of The New York Times, which first sought the documents in January. âTogether, the lawsuit and the warrant draw back the curtain on one of the governmentâs signature insider trading investigations, showing the breadth of suspicion surrounding Level Global, but also they also raise new questions about whether some of the <b>governmentâs aggressive tactics crossed a line</b>,â DealBook writes. Within months of the raid, Level Global shut its doors and shed about 80 jobs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>The government never charged Mr. Ganek</b>, though they labeled him an âunindicted co-conspirator.â His lawsuit contends that the warrant underpinning the raid âfalsely representedâ that Mr. Ganek was involved in insider trading. In responding to Mr. Ganekâs lawsuit, the United States attorneyâs office is likely to argue that the raids were necessary, a point the F.B.I. made in the warrant application. At the time, the government suspected that traders, heeding media reports of the looming investigation, were destroying emails and other evidence.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>STANDARD CHARTERED OVERHAULS LEADERSHIP</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The British bank Standard Chartered responded on Thursday to shareholdersâ calls for change, announcing a sweeping management overhaul including the departure of its chief executive, its chairman, the head of Asian markets and several directors, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/02/27/business/dealbook/standard-chartered-chief-executive-bill-winters-peter-sands.html">Jenny Anderson and Chad Bray write in DealBook</a>. In a move that surprised many, it named William T. Winters, the 53-year-old former head of JPMorgan Chaseâs investment bank â who was once seen as a candidate to succeed Jamie Dimon â to take the helm.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Winters, who will join the bank on May 1 and become chief executive in June, will succeed Peter Sands, one of the longest-serving chief executives in British finance. He will receive a base salary of 1.15 million pounds, or about $1.8 million, as well as a pension and other benefits. As the bankâs leader, <b>Mr. Winters will not have it easy</b>. The bank has been hurt in recent years by regulatory fines and investigations and by its focus on emerging markets. It has slashed thousands of jobs, closed its stock trading and underwriting unit and is looking to cut $400 million in costs. Impairments for bad loans, including in the mining sector, have soared.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Mr. Winters, an American, appears up to the task. In a call with reporters, John W. Peace, the chairman, said that Mr. Winters had âgreat respect among regulators, clients and the marketâ and a solid understanding of the global regulatory environment. Temasek Holdings, which owns almost 18 percent of Standard Chartered, declined to comment on whether it had pressed for management changes. But it said that it welcomed Mr. Winters, who âbrings with him considerable experience, as well as an excellent reputation for building good teams.â</p>
